tldr: The user had multiple duplicate Vercel projects for their
  sleep-questionnaire app. I helped them delete the extra projects and then
  guided them through setting up a development environment using a new
  branch with Vercel's preview deployments and existing environment variables.
overview: The user started by pointing out an issue with multiple duplicate
  Vercel projects for their "sleep-questionnaire" application. I identified the
  duplicates and, upon their request, proceeded to delete four of the five
  redundant projects, leaving only the primary one. Following this, the user
  inquired about setting up a development environment with a separate domain and
  environment variables. I recommended creating a  branch and
  leveraging Vercel's preview deployment features. I then created and pushed the
   branch to their GitHub repository. When the user asked to push local
  environment variables, I checked the Vercel configuration and found that the
  key variables were already set for the "Preview" environment, which would
  automatically apply to deployments from the  branch. I informed the
  user of this and provided clear instructions on how to configure a custom
  domain for the  branch and manage environment variables within the
  Vercel dashboard.
